article.headline: Sonics blow 11-point lead, but win
article.linkText: Sonics' lead goes boom, but they beat Hornets
article.story: NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- When the New Orleans Hornets finally slowed down Rashard Lewis and Ray Allen, Brent Barry stepped up to send a message that the Seattle SuperSonics weren't about to fold. Barry's straightaway 3-pointer with 4:21 to go snapped a 12-0 Hornets run and put Seattle back in the lead for good in the streaking SuperSonics' 91-80 victory Friday night. "I usually get my opportunities because of Ray and Rashard, and tonight they didn't stop either one of those two guys, so we just take what we can get," said Barry, whose team has won four straight, all on the road. "If you're going to make one shot, better make it a big one." Lewis scored 31 points, including a 20-foot jump shot and six free throws after Barry's 3, while Allen had 19. Vitaly Potapenko gave Seattle an unexpected edge inside with 14 points and 10 rebounds. The Sonics blew an 11-point fourth-quarter lead before Barry's basket sparked a 17-5 run to close out the game. "We're making plays when we need to and have won some tough games," said Seattle coach Nate McMillan, whose team held off Memphis a night earlier after briefly losing a double-digit lead in the final period. Baron Davis led New Orleans with 25 points, but periodic shooting droughts left him at 9-of-24 from the floor. Jamaal Magloire added 13 points and David Wesley 12, including consecutive 3-pointers during the run that gave New Orleans a brief 75-74 lead with 5:12 left. Seattle trailed throughout the first half, but opened the third period with a 9-0 run on a 3-pointer by Allen and two more by Lewis to take a 47-41 lead. Although McMillan predicted New Orleans would have an advantage in rebounding and inside play, the Sonics were able use a zone defense to deny New Orleans decent inside looks at the basket for long stretches. New Orleans, which did not go to the foul line once in the second or third quarters, got into trouble settling for outside shots, and at one point in the third quarter was 2-of-17 from 3-point range. The Hornets finished 6-of-29 from long range. "We didn't get inside as much as we could have," Hornets forward P.J. Brown said. "We were a little jump shot happy and it played right into their hands." Seattle ended up outscoring New Orleans inside 40-32 and finished with a 44-34 rebounding advantage. The Sonics shot 46 percent, while holding New Orleans to only 39 percent (32-of-82). "I thought the effort was there. I just think we were inefficient on the offensive end," Hornets coach Tim Floyd said. "They made some adjustments defensively that really bothered us." And Floyd added that the Hornets had no answer for Lewis, who shot 11-of-16. He was able several times to get open on cuts and convert passes into soaring jams without having to dribble. He also hit from outside and made 7-of-9 free throws. "They were guarding me one-on-one and nobody was really shadowing around me, so I was able to just kind of move around the pick, get a good screen and get wide open shots," Lewis said. "My jump shot was falling and my post game was going, too, so once I get both of them rolling it's kind of hard to contain." Potapenko gave Magloire fits by moving well without the ball and finished 7-of-11 shooting.< ^Notes: Lewis and Allen were the only Sonics to score through the first 11 minutes of the game, at which point Seattle trailed 27-15. ... Ronald Murray had 11 points off the bench for Seattle. ... Magloire, who finished with eight rebounds, was held without a double-double for only the fourth time in 15 games. ... The Hornets, which had won their previous game over Philadelphia, failed to get consecutive victories for the first time since beating the Los Angeles Clippers and Indiana on Feb. 25 and 27.
